    "title": "Mulligatawny",
    "subtitle": "The Anglo-Indian spiced soup that travelled home from Madras",
    "excerpt": "A rich, mildly spiced soup of chicken, lentils, and aromatic vegetables, thickened with coconut milk. The British-Indian version of a Tamil pepper water, sweetened and enriched over two centuries of adaptation.",
    "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861) ,  Project Gutenberg #10136. Mulligatawny soup, both thin and thick versions. This recipe follows the enriched thick version with coconut milk.\n\nEliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845) ,  Project Gutenberg. Mulligatawny entry.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Mulligatawny",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmpry0d1g00001wv4vuxbk5sw"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " started as a thin, spiced pepper broth from south India. British cooks took it home and made it richer: thickened with lentils, finished with coconut milk, and gentled in its spice balance. The name comes from the Tamil for pepper water. What settled into British home cooking is the enriched version, and that is what this recipe follows.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
