        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Build the spiced base",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Melt {{unsalted-butter}} of butter in a large saucepan over a medium-low heat. Add the {{onion}} onion, {{carrot}} carrot, and {{celery}} celery. Cook for 10 minutes until softened.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the {{garlic}} of garlic and {{ginger-root}} of ginger. Cook for 1 minute. Add the {{cumin-ground}} of ground cumin, {{coriander-seeds}} of ground coriander, and {{turmeric}} of turmeric. Stir and cook for 30 seconds.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Simmer and blend",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the {{lentils-red}} of red lentils and {{chicken-breast}} chicken breasts. Pour over {{stock-chicken}} of hot chicken stock. Bring to a simmer and cook for 20 minutes until the lentils have dissolved and the chicken is cooked through.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Lift the chicken breasts out of the pot. Blend the soup until smooth with a stick blender.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Shred the chicken into pieces and stir back into the soup. Pour in {{coconut-milk}} of coconut milk. Add the {{lemon-juice}} of lemon juice. Taste and adjust salt.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Ladle into bowls. Serve with steamed basmati rice, which can be stirred directly into the soup or eaten alongside.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Thin with hot water or extra stock, 100 ml at a time, until it pours easily. Taste and re-season after each addition.",
                "cause": "The lentils absorbed more liquid than expected.",
                "symptom": "Soup is too thick"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Always bloom the spices in the fat for at least 30 seconds before adding liquid. Use ground spices within six months of opening.",
                "cause": "Old ground spices, or they were not cooked in the fat long enough to develop.",
                "symptom": "Spice flavour is muted"
              },
              {
                "fix": "This doesn't affect the taste, only the appearance. To prevent it, lower the heat before adding the coconut milk and stir steadily.",
                "cause": "The soup was too hot when the coconut milk was added.",
                "symptom": "Coconut milk has curdled slightly"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Add a good twist of black pepper and a small pinch of cayenne or chilli flakes. The original Tamil version was specifically a pepper broth; a little heat is authentic.",
                "cause": "Not enough pepper or the spice quantities were conservative.",
                "symptom": "Soup is too mild"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Mulligatawny has an unusual history. It was brought back by soldiers and civil servants who had worked in south India and wanted something like the peppery broths they had eaten there. British cooks adapted it with what they had: thickened with lentils or flour, enriched with cream or coconut milk, sweetened in its spice profile. What emerged was something neither quite Indian nor quite British. Victorian household cookbooks listed it as a standard soup, and it has stayed in British kitchens ever since.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
